               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-190-person1779">
                  ELIZABETH 
                  GOODSON
               <interp inst="t18270913-190-person1779" type="surname" value="GOODSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-190-person1779" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-190-person1779" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Robert Goodson - he lives in <placeName id="t18270913-190-crimeloc1077">Rosemond-street, Clerkenwell</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-190-crimeloc1077" type="placeName" value="Rosemond-street, Clerkenwell"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-190-crimeloc1077" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-190-off1075 t18270913-190-crimeloc1077"></join>. Between two and three o'clock in the afternoon of the 25th of July, I was sweeping the parlour, and on turning round I saw the prisoner on the wrong side of the counter; he appeared to be returning from the till; I was frightened, and let him go: I then called Watkins out of the bake-house, who pursued - he ran down Corporation-lane, but was taken; he had taken two handsfull of silver, and left the till open: there was 8s. 6d. found on him, but I missed more than that; I had seen the till safe not two minutes before. The prisoner was a stranger to me.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-190-person1780">
                  THOMAS 
                  WATKINS
               <interp inst="t18270913-190-person1780" type="surname" value="WATKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-190-person1780" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-190-person1780" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prosecutrix called me - I pursued the prisoner, and caught him in Ashford-street; he had 8s. 6d. in his hand; he offered it to me, but I refused to take it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-190-person1781">
                  GEORGE 
                  HEFFER
               <interp inst="t18270913-190-person1781" type="surname" value="HEFFER"></interp>
